                <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-blue-600 mb-4">Focus for Learning</h2>
                <p class="text-slate-600 mb-6">This introductory lesson is designed to establish a firm conceptual foundation. By the end of this lesson, students will be able to:</p>
                <ul class="space-y-3 list-inside">
                    <li class="flex items-start">
                        <span class="text-blue-600 font-bold mr-2">&#10004;</span>
                        <span class="flex-1"><strong class="text-slate-900">Define</strong> work in the scientific sense.</span>
                    </li>
                    <li class="flex items-start">
                        <span class="text-blue-600 font-bold mr-2">&#10004;</span>
                        <span class="flex-1"><strong class="text-slate-900">Identify</strong> the two conditions necessary for work to be done.</span>
                    </li>
                    <li class="flex items-start">
                        <span class="text-blue-600 font-bold mr-2">&#10004;</span>
                        <span class="flex-1"><strong class="text-slate-900">Differentiate</strong> between the "everyday" meaning of work (effort) and the physics definition.</span>
                    </li>
                    <li class="flex items-start">
                        <span class="text-blue-600 font-bold mr-2">&#10004;</span>
                        <span class="flex-1"><strong class="text-slate-900">Define</strong> energy as the ability to do work.</span>
                    </li>
                    <li class="flex items-start">
                        <span class="text-blue-600 font-bold mr-2">&#10004;</span>
                        <span class="flex-1"><strong class="text-slate-900">State</strong> that the unit for both work and energy is the Joule (J).</span>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <div id="content-analysis" class="tab-content">
                <p class="text-slate-600 mb-6 text-center text-lg">This plan is not generic. It's a direct response to data from past assessments and an understanding of this specific class.</p>
                <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
                    <div class="card">
                        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-blue-600 mb-4">Data-Driven Goals</h2>
                        <p class="text-slate-600 mb-4">Analysis of previous student assessments revealed two primary conceptual weaknesses that this lesson will directly reinforce:</p>
                        <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 mb-4 text-red-700 font-medium">
                            <li>Struggles with concepts of net force.</li>
                            <li>Difficulty identifying *when* work is being done on a system.</li>
                        </ul>
                        <div class="chart-container">
                            <canvas id="weaknessChart"></canvas>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="card">
                        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-blue-600 mb-4">Student Profile & Needs</h2>
                        <p class="text-slate-600 mb-4">The class is a mix of average to above-average students with a distinct learning profile:</p>
                        <div class="bg-blue-50 p-4 rounded-lg mb-4">
                            <p class="font-semibold text-blue-900">Key Insight:</p>
                            <p class="text-blue-800">Students often struggle with abstract concepts but are strong with "plug and chug" algebraic calculations.</p>
                        </div>
                        <p class="text-slate-600 mb-4">This lesson plan is **differentiated** to meet this profile head-on by building conceptual understanding *before* introducing formulas.</p>
                        <div class_id="differentiation-links">
                            <button onclick="showTab('activities')" class="mt-2 w-full text-left px-4 py-3 bg-slate-200 text-slate-800 rounded-lg hover:bg-slate-300 transition-colors">
